"1197–Female":"1197–Overleden","1198–Female":"1198–Overleden","1142–Male":"1142–Overleden","1144–Female":"1144–Overleden","about 1193":"circa 1193","about 1191":"circa 1191","1198":"1198","1165":"1165","1142":"1142","1197":"1197","1185":"1185","1193":"1193","1191":"1191","1226":"1226","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1233":"1233","Abt 1165":"circa 1165","1144":"1144","about 1198":"circa 1198","about 1185":"circa 1185","about 1197":"circa 1197","Bulkeley, Cheshire, England":"Bulkeley, Cheshire, England","of Bulkeley, Cheshire, England":"Bulkeley, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1165–1226":"about 1165–1226","1165–1226":"1165–1226","1165–Female":"1165–Deceased","1185–1233":"1185–1233","1191–Female":"1191–Deceased","1193–Female":"1193–Deceased","1197–Female":"1197–Deceased","1198–Female":"1198–Deceased","1142–Male":"1142–Deceased","1144–Female":"1144–Deceased","about 1193":"about 1193","about 1191":"about 1191","1198":"1198","1165":"1165","1142":"1142","1197":"1197","1185":"1185","1193":"1193","1191":"1191","1226":"1226","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1233":"1233","Abt 1165":"about 1165","1144":"1144","about 1198":"about 1198","about 1185":"about 1185","about 1197":"about 1197","Bulkeley, Cheshire, England":"Bulkeley, Cheshire, England","of Bulkeley, Cheshire, England":"Bulkeley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bulkeley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Cheshire named Bulkeley, from Old English <i>bulluc</i> ‘bullock’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","History: Peter Bulkeley (1583–1659), Puritan divine, who came from Bedfordshire, England, was a founder of Concord, MA, in 1636."],"variants":[{"name":"Bulkley","meanings":["English (Hampshire): variant of   Bulkeley  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":50,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":59,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Bulkeley was born about 1165, in Bulkeley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Gilbert de Lande Patrick, was 25 and his mother, Mrs. Gilbert de Lande Patrick, was 23. He married Felicia de Chulmundelegh in 1185, in Bulkeley, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least